.0160441.t005", "bbox": [45.5, 678.7, 186.2, 690.1]}, {"text": "and inhibited, directly or indirectly, by other photoreceptors [41]. The broadband sensitivity of", "bbox": [252.5, 708.3, 725.7, 722.2]}, {"text": "R1-6 suggests that they are suitable for discriminating light intensities. It is theoretically possi-", "bbox": [252.5, 724.7, 721.7, 738.6]}, {"text": "ble to reduce redundancy in the signals of overlapping spectral sensitivities by subtracting the", "bbox": [252.5, 741.0, 717.6, 755.0]}, {"text": "signals of narrowband receptors from those of broadband receptors [42]. This process probably", "bbox": [252.5, 757.5, 727.2, 771.4]}, {"text": "enables the flies to extract heterogeneity in the wavelength distribution of light.", "bbox": [252.5, 773.9, 645.9, 787.8]}, {"text": "The natural enemies, including the parasitoid flies, are regarded as alternatives to pesticides", "bbox": [267.6, 790.3, 722.7, 804.2]}, {"text": "in IPM. There have been attempts to attract and retain natural enemies in agricultural fields,", "bbox": [252.5, 806.8, 712.3, 820.7]}, {"text": "but no effective methods have yet been established for parasitoid flies. Because many insects", "bbox": [252.5, 823.1, 710.1, 837.1]}, {"text": "are attracted to UV or GR, VL is a promising candidate for selectively attracting E. japonica to", "bbox": [252.5, 839.5, 720.5, 853.5]}, {"text": "the agricultural field [18]. Additional behavioral experiments in the field are necessary to", "bbox": [252.5, 855.9, 694.7, 869.9]}, {"text": "exploit the unique nature of this species for controlling lepidopteran pests.", "bbox": [252.5, 872.4, 622.9, 886.3]}, {"text": "PLOS ONE | DOI:10.1371/journal.pone.0160441 August 17, 2016 13 / 16", "bbox": [45.5, 945.2, 727.3, 956.7]}]}